      <h2>Quick Decision Guide</h2>

      <p><strong>Choose fiberglass if:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>You work as an electrician, HVAC tech, or any trade near live electrical equipment.</li>
        <li>You work on commercial job sites where OSHA requires non-conductive ladders near electrical hazards.</li>
        <li>You work around overhead power lines (exterior electrical service, tree trimming near lines, solar installation).</li>
        <li>You want a single ladder that is safe in any environment, regardless of electrical exposure.</li>
        <li>You prioritize lifetime durability over weight savings.</li>
      </ul>

      <p><strong>Choose aluminum if:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>Your work is 100% on exterior structures with no electrical hazard — roofing, siding, framing, general demolition.</li>
        <li>You carry your ladder long distances and every pound of weight savings matters for your daily energy expenditure.</li>
        <li>You need a telescoping or multi-position ladder for a service van — these are only available in aluminum.</li>
        <li>You are buying a dedicated ladder for tasks that never involve electricity and you want the best value per dollar.</li>
      </ul>

      <p><strong>Buy both if:</strong> You are a general contractor or service company that works mixed environments. One fiberglass step ladder and one aluminum multi-position ladder cover every job site scenario. The combined investment (approximately $200-$300 total) is less than the cost of one accident or one OSHA citation.</p>

      <h2>Bottom Line: The Material Decision Is a Safety Decision</h2>
      <p>If there is any chance you or your crew will work near electricity — and on a commercial job site, that chance exists even if it is not your primary task — buy fiberglass. The weight penalty is real but manageable. The electrical safety benefit is absolute.</p>

      <p>If your work is genuinely electrical-free — new-construction framing, exterior siding, metal roofing — aluminum is the better choice for its lighter weight, lower cost, and gradual failure mode. Just be honest about what "electrical-free" means on your job sites. Overhead service drops, temporary power poles, and exposed conductors during rough-in are all electrical hazards that an aluminum ladder turns into a life-threatening conductor.</p>

      <p>When in doubt, fiberglass. A 10-pound weight penalty beats a 10,000-volt surprise.</p>

